<!-- ══ SECTION 1: Overview ══ -->

<section class="content-section" id="overview">
  <div class="container-narrow">
    <p class="direct-answer">A ventral hernia is a bulge through a weakness or opening in the front wall of the abdomen. Umbilical hernias (at the navel), incisional hernias (at a prior surgical scar), and epigastric hernias (between the navel and breastbone) are all types of ventral hernia. Surgery is the only way to permanently repair them &mdash; there is no brace, medication, or exercise that can close the opening.</p>

```
<p>Ventral hernias are among the most common conditions Dr. Kakarla treats. They range from small umbilical hernias that can be repaired in 30 minutes to complex incisional hernias requiring abdominal wall reconstruction. Dr. Kakarla tailors the approach &mdash; open, laparoscopic, or robotic &mdash; to the size, location, and complexity of your hernia.</p>

