```
<h3>Abdominal Binder</h3>
<p>An abdominal binder (supportive wrap) is provided after surgery. <strong>Wear it when you are up and active for the first 4 weeks.</strong> You do not need to wear it while sleeping or resting. The binder supports the repair, reduces swelling, and improves comfort during recovery.</p>

<div class="alert-emergency" style="margin-top:2rem">
  <p class="alert-emergency-title">When to call after surgery</p>
  <p><strong>Call our office first</strong> for: fever over 101.5&deg;F &middot; worsening pain at the hernia site &middot; increasing redness, swelling, or drainage from incisions &middot; a new bulge at or near the repair site &middot; inability to keep fluids down &middot; severe bloating. We can often evaluate you quickly and advise on next steps.</p>
  <p style="margin-top:.75rem"><strong>Call 911</strong> for: chest pain or difficulty breathing &middot; fainting &middot; sudden leg swelling with pain.</p>
  <p style="margin-top:.75rem;font-size:.85rem">For routine questions, call <a href="tel:(770) 962-9977" style="color:var(--red-700)">(770) 962-9977</a> during office hours.</p>
</div>

<h3 style="margin-top:2rem">Common Activity Questions</h3>
<div class="content-card">
  <ul class="prep-list">
    <li><strong>Driving</strong> &mdash; when off narcotic pain medication and comfortable (typically day 4&ndash;7)</li>
    <li><strong>Desk work</strong> &mdash; most return within 1&ndash;2 weeks</li>
    <li><strong>Physical labor</strong> &mdash; 4&ndash;6 weeks with gradual return</li>
    <li><strong>Lifting</strong> &mdash; nothing over 10 lbs for 4 weeks</li>
    <li><strong>Exercise</strong> &mdash; walking from day 1; gym/weights after 4 weeks with gradual increase</li>
    <li><strong>Sexual activity</strong> &mdash; when comfortable and off prescription pain medication</li>
    <li><strong>Showering</strong> &mdash; brief shower same day; no baths/pools until Dermabond sloughs off (5&ndash;10 days)</li>
    <li><strong>Abdominal binder</strong> &mdash; wear when active for 4 weeks; remove for sleep</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="content-card blue" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
  <h3 style="font-size:.88rem;margin-bottom:.5rem">Multimodal pain management</h3>
  <p style="font-size:.88rem;color:var(--stone-600);margin:0;line-height:1.6">Dr. Kakarla uses an ERAS-based (enhanced recovery using multiple non-opioid strategies) multimodal approach: TAP block during surgery, scheduled acetaminophen and ibuprofen after. Most patients manage recovery with over-the-counter medication alone.</p>
</div>
```

