<!-- ══ SECTION 12: Risks ══ -->

<section class="content-section alt" id="risks">
  <div class="container-narrow">
    <p class="section-label">Understanding the risks</p>
    <h2>Possible Risks and Complications</h2>
    <p>Ventral hernia repair is a common, well-studied operation. Serious complications are uncommon, but no surgery is risk-free:</p>
    <div class="content-card">
      <ul class="prep-list">
        <li><strong>Seroma</strong> (fluid collection at the hernia site) &mdash; common, usually resolves on its own. The body naturally fills the space where the hernia was. Most seromas are harmless and absorb over weeks</li>
        <li><strong>Hernia recurrence</strong> &mdash; can occur, especially in patients who are overweight, smoke, or have had multiple prior repairs. Risk is lower with mesh reinforcement and robotic technique</li>
        <li><strong>Infection</strong> &mdash; uncommon with minimally invasive technique</li>
        <li><strong>Bleeding or hematoma</strong> &mdash; usually minor and self-limited</li>
        <li><strong>Chronic pain</strong> &mdash; uncommon; most patients have less pain after repair than before</li>
        <li><strong>Mesh-related complications</strong> &mdash; rare; may include mesh infection or mesh migration</li>
        <li><strong>Bowel injury</strong> &mdash; rare</li>
        <li><strong>Blood clots</strong> &mdash; rare; early walking reduces risk</li>
        <li><strong>Conversion to open surgery</strong> &mdash; uncommon with robotic technique</li>
        <li><strong>Anesthesia risks</strong> &mdash; discussed with your anesthesiologist</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <p>Dr. Kakarla discusses your individual risk profile during consultation. Your specific risks, benefits, and alternatives are reviewed before you consent to surgery.</p>
    <p style="font-size:.88rem;color:var(--stone-500)">This information is general and may not apply to every patient. Your own risks, benefits, and recovery plan will be discussed with you in person before surgery.</p>
  </div>
</section>

